SIMPLE: erode
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Erode
<hw>E*rode"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Eroded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Eroding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>erodere</ets>,
<ets>erosum</ets>; <ets>e</ets> out + <ets>rodere</ets> to gnaw. See
<er>Rodent</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To eat into or away; to
corrode; <as>as, canker <ex>erodes</ex> the flesh</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The
blood . . . <xex>erodes</xex> the vessels.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Wiseman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The smaller charge is more apt to . . . <qex>erode</qex> the
gun.</q> <rj><qau>Am. Cyc.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Geol. & Phys. Geog.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>To
wear away; <as>as, streams and glaciers <ex>erode</ex> the
land</as>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>To produce by erosion, or wearing
away; <as>as, glaciers <ex>erode</ex>
<universbold>U</universbold>-shaped valleys</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>to reduce or lessen as if by eroding; <as>as, a
politician's base of support is <ex>eroded</ex> by evidence of
corruption; the buying power of the dollar is <ex>eroded</ex> by
inflation</as>.</def> <mark>[fig.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Eroded</ent>⟦br⟧
